<li id="cite_note-24"><b><a href="#cite_ref-24" title="">^</a></b> In connection with the Lord's Supper, some Mennonites practice <a href="/wiki/Feet_washing" title="Feet washing" class="mw-redirect">feet washing</a> as continuing outer sign of humility within the church. Feet washing was not originally an Anabaptist practice. Pilgram Marpeck before 1556 included it, and it became widespread in the late 1500s and the 1600s. Today it is practiced by some as a memorial sacrament, in memory of Christ washing the feet of his disciples as recorded in the thirteenth chapter of the Gospel of John.</li>
